section.subsection:
                The addition and the multiplication functions perform addition and multiplication operations in rings and
                fields. For groups of points on an elliptic curve, such as the G1 and G2 groups associated with
                pairings, both addition and multiplication represent the group operation (and similarly both
                0
                and
                1
                represent the identity element).

                In contrast, the GT group is currently implemented as a subgroup of a finite field, so only
                multiplicative operations should be used for GT.

                /* Performs the addition between element and a.*/
Element a = element.getField().newRandomElement();
element.add(a);


                /* Performs the substraction between element and a.
Element a = element.getField().newRandomElement();
element.sub(a);


                /* Performs the multiplication between element and a. */
Element a = element.getField().newRandomElement();
element.mul(a);


                /* Performs the multiplication between element and an int. */
element.mul(5);


                /* Performs the multiplication between element and a BigInteger. */
element.mul(new BigInteger("5"));


                /* Performs the multiplication between element and z
where z must be an element of a integer mod ring (i.e. Zn for some n). */
Element z = pairing.getZr().newRandomElement();
element.mulZn(z);


                /* Performs the division between element and a. */
Element a = element.getField().newRandomElement();
element.div(a);


                /* Performs the doubling of the element. */
element.twice();


                /* Performs the halving of the element. */
element.halve();


                /* Performs the inversion of the element. */
element.invert();


                /* Performs the squaring of the element. */
element.square();


                /* Performs the negation of the element. */
element.negate();


                /* Performs the square root of the element. */
element.sqrt();

subsection.source:
/* Raises element to a z which must be an element of a integer mod ring (i.e. Zn for some n). */
Element z = pairing.getZr().newRandomElement();
element.powZn(z);

section.subsection:


                    If it knows in advance that a particular value (in G1) will be raised several times
                    then time can be saved in the long run by first calling the preprocessing function.


                    The interface to be used is the
                    it.unisa.dia.gas.jpbc.ElementPowPreProcessing


                /* Prepare element to be raised and store preprocessing information in ppp.
element will be not modified in any way.*/

ElementPowPreProcessing ppp = element.pow();

/* Now let's raise using ppp which returns a new element which contains the result of the operation. */

Element out = ppp.pow(BigInteger.valueOf(5));

out = ppp.pow(pairing.getZr().newRandomElement());


                The result of the precomputation can be stored to be used later.
                The following code convert ppp to a byte array:

                    byte[] pppBytes = ppp.toBytes();

                To convert the byte array to an instance of the ElementPowPreProcessing interface
                use the following code:

ElementPowPreProcessing ppp = element.getField().pow(pppBytes);

subsection.source:
/* Converts element to bytes. The number of bytes it will write can be determined
calling getLengthInBytes(). */
byte[] bytes = element.toBytes();

/* Reads element from the buffer source, starting from the passed offset,
and returns the number of bytes read. */
element.setFromBytes(bytes, 13);

/* Returns the immutable version of the element.
* When an element is immutable it means that every call to a method which modifies the value
* of the element returns a new instance of the element and not the same one.
*/
Element immutable = element.getImmutable();
